{{Infobox serial killer | name=Cincinnati Strangler | image=Cincinnati Strangler.jpg | caption=Posteal Laskey Jr., the man believed to be the "Cincinnati Strangler" | birth_name=Posteal Laskey Jr. | occupation = former cab driver | birth_date=1938 | birth_place= | death_date={{death date and age|2007|6|29|1938}} | death_place = [[Pickaway Correctional Institution]] in [[Scioto Township, Pickaway County, Ohio]] | victims=7 | country=United States | states=[[Ohio]] | beginyear=1965 | endyear=1966 | apprehended=December 1966 | penalty=[[Death penalty|Death]], commuted to [[life imprisonment]] by ''[[Furman v. Georgia]]'' }}
The '''Cincinnati Strangler''' was the name given to a [[serial killer]] who [[rape]]d, then [[strangling|strangled]] seven mostly elderly women in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] between 1965 and 1966. The identity of the Cincinnati Strangler is commonly believed to be former cab driver [[Posteal Laskey Jr]].<!-- References to Laskey's race is irrelevant to the article; inclusion of his race is considered vandalism. -->{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}
During the killing spree there was considerable alarm on the part of many Cincinnatians, with locksmiths and hardware stores unable to keep up with the demand for locks.<ref name="Post Perry">{{cite news | authorlink = Kimball Perry | last = Perry | first = Kimball | title = Outrage Grows to release of Killer | work = [[The Cincinnati Post]] | date = March 1, 2002 | url = http://www.cincypost.com/2002/mar/01/lasky030102.html | accessdate = February 22, 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050309215503/http://www.cincypost.com/2002/mar/01/lasky030102.html | archivedate = March 9, 2005 }}</ref> Despite being charged with only one murder, the citywide panic only abated after Laskey's arrest and conviction, when the killings suddenly stopped, thus supporting investigators' claim that they successfully found and jailed the Cincinnati Strangler.
Originally sentenced to [[capital punishment in the United States|death]], Laskey's sentence was commuted to [[life imprisonment]] when the [[United States Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] invalidated the death penalty in ''[[Furman v. Georgia]]''. In February 2007, Laskey was denied [[parole]]. The grounds cited by the Ohio Parole Board included the heinous nature of the crime, Laskey's prior record, and the community disapproval of an early release.<ref>{{cite news | last = Coolidge | first = Sharon | authorlink = | date = February 14, 2007 | title = No Parole For Strangler | work = [[The Cincinnati Post]] | url = http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070214/NEWS01/702140349/1077/COL02 | accessdate = February 23, 2007 }}</ref>
He would have been eligible for parole again in 2017 at the age of 79 years and was incarcerated in the [[Pickaway Correctional Institution]]. Laskey died on May 29, 2007 of natural causes, while still in prison. No one claimed his body and prison officials said he was buried in one of the State of Ohio's prison cemeteries.
