{{Infobox person | name = Julius Drum | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1958|03|18}} | birth_place = [[Winnebago, Nebraska]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2007|09|17|1958|03|18}} | death_place = [[Macy, Nebraska]] | nationality = [[Omaha people]], [[Ho-Chunk]], [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] | other_names = Julius Corder | occupation = Actor | known_for = ''[[Thunderheart]]'', ''[[Dark Blood]]'' }} '''Julius Drum''' (March 18, 1958&ndash; September 17, 2007), also known as Julius L. Corder, was a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] actor.
Born in [[Winnebago, Nebraska]], Drum was adopted at the age of five by John and Dorothy Corder of [[McCook, Nebraska]]. Upon graduating from school, he entered medical school in California and supported himself as a [[Television advertisement|television commercial]] actor. He was a member of the [[Screen Actors Guild]].<ref>{{cite web | last =Bogard | first =Kenneth D. | title =Julius L. Corder | work =Find A Grave Memorial# 22841203 | publisher =Find A Grave | date =November 12, 2007 | url =https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/22841203&ref=acom | accessdate = August 16, 2014}}</ref>
Drum played Richard Yellow Hawk in the 1992 movie, ''[[Thunderheart]]''. He also acted in the 2012 movie, ''[[Dark Blood]]'', although the movie was not released during Drum's lifetime.
He had been involved with the [[Lincoln Indian Center]] and was active in the [[American Indian Movement]]. He received the Outstanding New Performer award from [[First Americans in the Arts]] for his work in ''Thunderheart''.<ref>{{cite web | title =Julius Drum Jr. aka Josh Drum. Richard Yellow Hawk on Thunderheart | work =Bits and Pieces 3 | publisher =NativeCelebs | url =http://www.nativecelebs.com/profiles/bits_and_pieces3.htm | accessdate = August 16, 2014}}</ref>
Complications from [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetes]] forced Drum to seek help at the [[Carl T. Curtis Health Center]] in [[Macy, Nebraska]]. He died at the center on September 17, 2007.<ref>{{cite web | title =Julius L. Corder | work =Obituaries | publisher =McCook Gazette | date =November 9, 2007 | url =http://www.mccookgazette.com/story/1289966.html | accessdate = August 16, 2014}}</ref>
